In Java objects are not directly callable. You need to invoke a method on the instance:

    s.aiMethod();

If you want to pass a method as a parameter then you&#39;ll need to use a method reference. A method reference allows you to cast a method to an interface with a single method, as long as the return type and parameters are compatible. 

In this case you could use the `java.lang.Runnable` interface: 

    public interface Runnable {
        public abstract void run();
    }

You can refactor your method to accept a method reference easily:

    public static void AISteps(Runnable method){
        for(int i = 0; i &lt; 19; i++){
            for(int j = 0; j &lt; 19; j++){
                if(Main.index[i][j] == &quot;+ &quot;){
                   if(Main.winner == &quot;&quot;)
                        method.run();
                }   
            }
        }
    }

Now you should be able to call it like this for a static method:

    AISteps(AIClass::someMethod);

The same rule applies if the method is an instance method:

    AIClass myAIClass = ...;
    AISteps(myAIClass::someMethod);

Have you considered passing `lambdas` to your method and have them called?  Here is a simple example.

```java
   public static void main(String[] args) {
	  AISteps(() -&gt; System.out.println(&quot;Doit!&quot;));
	  AISteps(() -&gt; System.out.println(&quot;finished!&quot;));
   }

   public static void AISteps(Runnable fnc) {
	  for (int i = 0; i &lt; 2; i++) {
		 for (int j = 0; j &lt; 2; j++) {
			/// do some processing here
			fnc.run();
		 }
	  }
   }
```

Read up on functional references and lambdas to see the various options you can use.

