Communications rely on agreed upon protocols. TCP and other similar protocols wrap and unwrap data in protocol layers (see the [OSI model][1]) as data is transmitted from source to destination.

Let&#39;s rewrite the code to make it more readable and efficient.

    package main
    
    import &quot;fmt&quot;
    
    func MakeCMD(inst string) []byte {
    	cmd := make([]byte, 0, 2+len(inst)+1)
    	cmd = append(cmd, &#39;\xFF&#39;)
    	cmd = append(cmd, &#39;\xFF&#39;)
    	cmd = append(cmd, inst...)
    	cmd = append(cmd, &#39;\n&#39;)
    	return cmd
    }
    
    func main() {
    	inst := &quot;XYZ&quot;
    	fmt.Printf(&quot;%q\n&quot;, MakeCMD(inst))
    }

Playground: https://play.golang.org/p/--RnhF1b37A

Output:

    &quot;\xff\xffXYZ\n&quot;

It looks like data (&quot;XYZ&quot;) is wrapped in flow-control bytes, like newline (`&#39;\n&#39;`) to terminate the data.

You need to look at the IOT device specification to interpret the data sent to the IOT device. What communications protocol is the IOT device using?

  [1]: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/OSI_model

